{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"Q4HYS3KnY4wBx43SroID9rSuCu8=","kind":"spec","title":"kref local-file tracking — B1: tracking state \u0026 scoping — design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"EEmsFb/v8qR4aFw1Ik9cXEVN44A=","body":"# kref local-file tracking — B1: tracking state \u0026 scoping — design\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-25\n**Status:** IMPLEMENTED on branch `feat/file-tracking-b1` (code is now the source\nof truth). Two deviations made during implementation: (1) the ignore mechanism is\n`.git/info/exclude`, not a committed `.gitignore` — unifying with/renaming the\npre-existing `EnsureGitignore` → `EnsureKrefIgnored`; (2) floaters anchor at\n`.kref/\u003cbasename\u003e` (auto-disambiguated), not the illustrative `.kref/foo/bar.md`.\n**Scope:** The foundation phase of \"keep an entry synced with a local file.\"\nB1 adds the per-entry **tracking state**, the repo-relative **path label**, and\nthe `.kref/` floater anchor + ignore plumbing. It does **not** add reconcile,\ndrift detection, or write-back — those are later phases (§7).\n\n## 1. Context\n\nThis is phase 1 of a larger, deliberately decomposed feature. The motivating\nneed: a user keeps loose markdown files and wants kref to keep them synced\n*without* having to commit those files into a git repo. kref already provides\nthe durable, syncable home (entries live in the repo's `kref-*` ref namespaces);\nwhat is missing is an explicit, per-entry link to a working-copy file plus the\noperations that act on it.\n\nDecomposition (each its own brainstorm → spec → plan):\n\n- **B1 (this spec)** — tracking state + scoping (the keystone).\n- **B2** — targeted reconcile (file → entry) via `kref reconcile`.\n- **B3** — drift detection / visibility in `list` and `show`.\n- **B4** — write-back (entry → file) with a `git merge-file` conflict model.\n\n**Locked identity model** (the central decision this feature turned on): kref's\nexisting `kref-id` **trailer is the identity** — it behaves like a filesystem\n*inode* (survives moves, dedups, and already retains every version through the\ngit-bug append-only op log, recoverable via `kref diff`). The file **path is a\nsoft, mutable label** — like a filename, not an identity. We deliberately did\n**not** adopt a \"shadow filesystem\" model where the path is an identity slot:\nthat would be a second identity model competing with the trailer (violating the\n\"one concept, one verb\" guidance) and would commit us to a versioned\nfilesystem's worth of `mv`/`rm`/`cp` semantics. Path-as-label keeps kref a\ncontent store with location hints.\n\n**What already exists and is reused:**\n\n- `store.Init`/`Open` require an existing git repo and search upward for `.git`,\n  so \"the repo root\" is always well-defined (`internal/store/store.go:38-46`).\n- `s.RepoRelative(path)` converts an absolute/cwd path to a repo-relative one\n  (already used by `Ingest` when recording provenance, `internal/bridge/\n  bridge.go`).\n- The op model: entries are mutated by appending ops (`SetKind`, `RecordOrigin`,\n  `Tombstone`, `Restore` — `internal/entry/operations.go`, `internal/store/\n  store.go:219,299,429`). B1 follows this precedent.\n- `OriginEvent.SourcePath` (`internal/entry/snapshot.go:16-19`) records ingest\n  *provenance* (append-only history). B1's tracked path is distinct: it is the\n  single, current, mutable working-copy location, not history.\n\n## 2. Goals / non-goals\n\n**Goals**\n\n- An entry can be explicitly marked **tracked**, carrying a repo-relative\n  **path label** to its working-copy file.\n- Pointing kref at a file **outside** the repo root (\"a floater\") copies it\n  under `.kref/\u003ctail\u003e` and tracks it there; `.kref/` is locally ignored.\n- A minimal command surface to set/clear tracking: `kref track` / `kref untrack`.\n\n**Non-goals**\n\n- No reconcile, drift detection, or write-back (B2–B4).\n- No promotion of the path to an identity (no path-collision-as-version, no\n  shadow filesystem, no `mv`/`rm`/`cp` semantics).\n- No change to the trailer mechanism or to `ingest`'s existing behavior.\n- No auto-tracking of `ingest`ed files yet — revisited in B2 where reconcile\n  gives it meaning.\n\n## 3. Data model\n\nAdd two ops to the entry op log, mirroring the existing op precedent:\n\n- `Track{Path string}` — sets the entry's tracked state and records the\n  repo-relative path label.\n- `Untrack{}` — clears the tracked state. The path label is cleared; the\n  working-copy file on disk is **left untouched** (never delete user data).\n\nThe snapshot (`internal/entry/snapshot.go`) gains:\n\n- `Tracked bool`\n- `TrackedPath string` — repo-relative; empty when `Tracked` is false.\n\nRationale for **storing** the path (vs. deriving it by scanning for the\ntrailer): explicit, O(1) to read, and the trailer remains the recovery\nmechanism if the label drifts (§3.3). Deriving-by-scan would make \"tracked\"\nimplicit and cost a repo walk on every read.\n\n### 3.1 In-repo vs. floater at track time\n\nGiven a path argument:\n\n- **Inside the repo root** → record `RepoRelative(path)` as `TrackedPath`; the\n  file stays where it is.\n- **Outside the repo root (floater)** → copy the file to `.kref/\u003ctail\u003e`, where\n  `\u003ctail\u003e` is the source's path tail; record `.kref/\u003ctail\u003e` as `TrackedPath`.\n  Because the path is a disposable label, a `.kref/` **filename clash with a\n  different entry's file** is resolved by auto-disambiguating the name\n  (`bar.md` → `bar-2.md`); it carries no semantic meaning and needs only to be\n  unique on disk.\n\n### 3.2 `.kref/` ignore plumbing\n\nThe first time a floater is created (or lazily, whenever `.kref/` is first\nwritten), append `.kref/` to `.git/info/exclude` **idempotently** (do not\nduplicate the line; check first). This is the repo-local, uncommitted ignore —\nchosen deliberately so the project's committed `.gitignore` is never touched.\nBecause `.git/info/exclude` does not travel between clones, kref re-applies it\nper machine. kref **announces** when it writes into `.git/` (touching git\ninternals is precisely the kind of side effect the good-CLI-defaults checks say\nto surface).\n\nExplicit tradeoff recorded so future work does not \"fix\" it: a committed\n`.gitignore` entry would travel across clones but would pollute the project\ntree; we chose clean-tree-over-portable for the ignore.\n\n### 3.3 Self-healing label\n\nThe `TrackedPath` label may go stale (the user moves the file). It is not an\nidentity, so this is not a correctness problem: the trailer in the file still\nresolves to the entry, so a later reconcile (B2) can rediscover the file and\nupdate `TrackedPath`. B1 only stores and clears the label; healing is a B2\nbehavior, noted here so the field's mutability is understood.\n\n## 4. Command surface\n\n- `kref track \u003cpath\u003e` — ensure there is an entry for `\u003cpath\u003e`, then mark it\n  tracked. This is the `kref add \u003cpath\u003e`-style one-step flow:\n  - If `\u003cpath\u003e` has a trailer resolving to an existing entry → mark that entry\n    tracked at its current location.\n  - If `\u003cpath\u003e` has **no trailer** (never ingested) → ingest it first (creating\n    the entry and writing its trailer, reusing the existing `Ingest` path),\n    then mark the new entry tracked. So `track` is \"ensure-entry + mark,\" not\n    \"mark a pre-existing entry only.\"\n  - If `\u003cpath\u003e` is outside the repo → perform the floater copy (§3.1) before\n    either of the above.\n  - If `\u003cpath\u003e` does not exist → an actionable, guided error (the style\n    established by the prior CLI-help work).\n\n  This quietly resolves the parked verb question for the track path: `track`\n  composes `ingest` + the new `Track` op, so the user never needs to ingest\n  first as a separate step.\n- `kref untrack \u003cid|path\u003e` — clear tracking for the resolved entry; the file on\n  disk is left in place.\n\nBoth commands follow the existing `argGuide`/`Example` conventions (every leaf\ncarries a worked example; missing-arg errors are actionable).\n\n## 5. Error handling\n\n- Non-existent path to `track` → guided error naming what is missing and a\n  worked example.\n- `track` on an already-tracked entry with a different path → re-point the\n  label (a `Track` op with the new path); announce the change.\n- `.kref/` filename clash → auto-disambiguate (§3.1).\n- `untrack` on an untracked entry → no-op with an informational message.\n- Floater copy I/O failure → surface the error; do not partially record\n  tracking state.\n\n## 6. Testing (ginkgo, existing suites)\n\n- `internal/store`: `Track` then snapshot shows `Tracked=true` + expected\n  `TrackedPath`; `Untrack` clears both; re-`Track` re-points the path; op log\n  retains history.\n- `RepoRelative` behavior for an in-repo path (recorded as-is) vs. a floater\n  (copied under `.kref/`, recorded as `.kref/\u003ctail\u003e`).\n- Floater filename clash auto-disambiguates without overwriting the existing\n  file.\n- `.git/info/exclude` gains `.kref/` exactly once across repeated track calls\n  (idempotent); the file on disk is untouched by `untrack`.\n- `cmd/kref`: `kref track`/`kref untrack` happy paths and the guided\n  non-existent-path error; both leaf commands carry an `Example`.\n\n## 7. Deferred (later phases)\n\n- **B2 — reconcile:** `kref reconcile` walks tracked entries and re-ingests from\n  their `TrackedPath` (idempotent, trailer-keyed); decides whether `ingest`\n  auto-marks files tracked; implements the §3.3 self-heal.\n- **B3 — drift:** store a content hash (`git hash-object`) at last sync; surface\n  in-sync/diverged in `list` and `show`.\n- **B4 — write-back:** entry → file, with conflicts resolved by a 3-way\n  `git merge-file` against the last-synced blob."}]}